"{\"uid\": \"theatlantic.com-health-archive-2024-07-olympics-photo-day-leap-through-antlers-679277\", \"text\": \"A unique view of a whimsical obstacle for riders in Versailles  One of the best parts about the Olympics can be the creativity and variety found in the arenas and courses. For the 2024 equestrian cross-country course, designer Pierre Le Goupil took inspiration from the features and grounds of the Palace of Versailles, creating 28 decorative obstacles-including this fence shaped like a stag's head, with antlers reaching up more than 23 feet (7 meters) on either side.  Here, Team Australia's Kevin McNab, riding the horse Don Quidam, clears the hurdle during the equestrian cross-country leg on day two of the 2024 Olympic Games at Chateau de Versailles in Versailles, France.  Previously:  July 28:A Fencer's Moment of Victory  July 27:A Towering Light Show at the Opening Ceremony  TheAtlantic.com \\u00a92026The Atlantic Monthly Group. All Rights Reserved.  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and the GooglePrivacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply\"}"